{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636272"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:26:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:26:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17578"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17578"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.03,0.13,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10268"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10268"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56844"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10073"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of HDL?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transports dietary lipids from intestine","Stores excess triglycerides","Synthesises new cholesterol molecules","Delivers cholesterol to peripheral tissues","Transports cholesterol from tissues to liver"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of HDL is \u003Cstrong\u003Etransport of cholesterol from peripheral tissues to the liver\u003C/strong\u003E through a process called reverse cholesterol transport. This process helps remove excess cholesterol from tissues and transport it to the liver for excretion or recycling, which contributes to HDL\u0027s cardioprotective effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelivers cholesterol to peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of low density lipoprotein (LDL), not HDL\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransports dietary lipids from intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of chylomicrons\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStores excess triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily done by adipose tissue, not lipoproteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesises new cholesterol molecules\u003C/strong\u003E - HDL transports cholesterol but does not synthesise it; cholesterol synthesis occurs primarily in the liver\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL particles are initially synthesised in the liver and intestine as protein-rich nascent particles. They then acquire cholesterol from peripheral tissues through the ATP-binding cassette transporter A1 (ABCA1) and mature into spherical particles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High density lipoprotein (HDL) removes excess cholesterol from peripheral tissues and transports it back to the liver.","HDL particles are synthesised in the liver and small intestine as protein-rich nascent particles.","The anti-atherogenic properties of HDL are primarily due to its role in reverse cholesterol transport."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Text